<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Ceanothus thyrsiflorus </i>is an obligate-seeding species that germinates from dormant seed banks after fire, and it dominates for decades. According to Ford (1991), in coastal environments after a long period free of burning, the <i>C. thyrsiflorus </i>cohorts released by disturbance become decadent, and the sites return to dominance by the typical shrubs of coastal scrub types.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (20-50 years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Seasonality</td>
			<td>Summer-early fall
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Size/extent</td>
			<td>Medium to large; up to and beyond stand
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Complexity</td>
			<td>Low to moderate
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
