    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Ceanothus thyrsiflorus</i> includes western the Klamath Mountains (M261Ab, As, Au) and Northern California Coast Ranges (M261B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ad-l). Stands differ in species composition with elevation, and they are replaced by stands of <i>Ceanothus oliganthus</i> above 600 m. Descriptions of the alliance come from Cone Peak Gradient RNA (Cheng 2004) and the Big Sur area (Bickford and Rich 1984, Engles and Genetti 1984).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ae). Stands occur in the western portion of this section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-b, Ad-m). Extensive stands established after the 1995 Mount Vision fire in Point Reyes National Seashore (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). Stands have been mapped within Sonoma County in the vicinity of Mt. St. Helena (Klein et al. 2015). Stands occur at Mt. Tamalpais Watershed and Soulajule Reservoir (Evens and Kentner 2006) and throughout Point Reyes and the adjacent Golden Gate National Recreation Area (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). These stands temporarily have replaced stands of either <i>Pinus muricata</i> or <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii.</i> Dense stands in the redwood belt establish in Humboldt Co. after logging, especially after burning slash.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb). Stands have been mapped within Sonoma County in the vicinity of Black Mountain (Klein et al. 2015).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bh). Stands of <i>Ceanothus arboreus</i> have been sampled on Santa Cruz (Rodriguez et al. 2017) and Santa Catalina Islands (Dixon et al. 2019).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Managers of industrial timberlands use herbicides and manual release techniques to speed up the return to conifer dominance, in spite of the fact that the shrubs affix nitrogen and enrich the soil. </div>
</div>

    

    

